column75: Narrative

The Portland Central City includes downtown, Goose Hollow, the Pearl and Lloyd Districts, the Inner Eastside as well as South Waterfront and Lower Albina. The Central City is home to professional service industries that support the entire region, a number of emerging business sectors that diversify the economy and support regional prosperity while acting as the regional center of governance, education, arts and culture, and a rapidly growing and diversifying population. This density of activity cannot be generated elsewhere, thus the Central City’s positive impact on economic development, creativity, civic engagement and livability of the region is significant. All five of the MAX Light Rail Lines, dozens of TriMet bus lines and the Portland Streetcar serve the Central City. Portland is currently finalizing the Central City 2035 planning project that is intended to preserve the existing assets and lead to a truly livable, sustainable city center—a place where equity is reflected in actions and decisions, youth can thrive and emerge as future leaders, and the heart of the city is prosperous, healthy and connected to the rest of the city and the region.

The Beaverton Regional Center is located just west of Highway 217 and is defined by SW Canyon Road and SW Beaverton-Hillsdale Highway/SW Farmington Road, along with the Portland and Western Railroad track that form distinct sections of the regional center. South of the railroad is the walkable older part of the city that is mostly residential and includes the library. The area along SW Canyon Road and SW Beaverton Hillsdale Highway, east of SW Lombard is composed mostly of large scale auto oriented commercial development. The resulting mix of commercial uses including shops and restaurants, make this regional center the commercial and retail hub for much of Beaverton and parts of unincorporated Washington County. The Beaverton Transit Center provides transit access via MAX Light Rail Red and Blue Lines, numerous TriMet bus lines and the northern terminus of the Westside Express Service Commuter Rail.

The Clackamas Regional Center is located in unincorporated Clackamas County along Interstate 205. Home to a large regional mall and many destination shops and services, the regional center serves as the retail hub for northern Clackamas County and much of East Portland. Auto-oriented development makes up the majority of the regional center, with large parking lots and major arterials making walking challenging. The regional center benefits from great transit access. The southern terminus of the MAX Light Rail Green Line and ten TriMet bus lines stop at the Clackamas Transit Center, which also has a park a ride facility. Columbia Area Transit, providing service to and from Hood River and The Dalles, also stops at the regional center. Clackamas County’s vision for the regional center includes a transition to even more intensive uses, better access for all modes of transportation, and a more attractive visual character.

The Gateway Regional Center is located in East Portland where Interstates 205 and 84 intersect. The regional center is home to the Gateway Transit Center where the MAX Light Rail Red, Blue, and Green lines and seven TriMet bus lines stop. Columbia Area Transit, providing service to and from Hood River and The Dalles, also stops at the transit center where there is a park and ride facility. Development in the area is a mix of housing types, primarily auto oriented retail and some institutional uses. This area is expected to become the most intensely developed area in Portland outside of the Central City and transform from a suburban low-density area to a mixed-use regional center that maximizes the public’s significant investment in the transportation infrastructure.

The Gresham Regional Center is located in downtown Gresham and is intended to serve eastern Multnomah County. The regional center is made up of two neighborhoods—the Civic Neighborhood and downtown Gresham—that have their own distinct characteristics. Downtown Gresham is the historic walkable core of the city and the Civic Neighborhood is a developing transit-oriented neighborhood. Throughout the regional center is a mix of uses, including commercial, office, civic and residential. The MAX Light Rail Blue Line has four stops within the regional center and terminates at the Cleveland Avenue Station. The area is also served by eight TriMet bus lines and a Sandy Area Metro bus line. Plans for the regional center envision an 18-hour mixed use district with the most intense development occurring within a ¼ mile of the MAX Light Rail stations.

The Hillsboro Regional Center includes historic downtown Hillsboro and a large surrounding area that includes a wide variety of residential, employment and commercial uses. The downtown area includes many civic and institutional uses such as the Washington County Court House, the Hillsboro Civic Center, the Washington County Public Services Building, Tuality Community Hospital and a satellite campus of Pacific University. The regional center has four MAX Light Rail Blue Line stations, including the terminus of the Blue Line at the Hatfield Government Station. Additionally, the area is served by four TriMet bus lines and a Washington County Bus Service line providing connections to Banks and North Plains. Portland and Western Railroad tracks run north-south and east-west through the regional center.

The Oregon City Regional Center is located along the Willamette River in the oldest incorporated city in Oregon. The historic downtown area which includes the Clackamas County Court House is cut off from the river by Highway 99E which traverses the entire center. There is significant amount of largely undeveloped parcels located within the center. The city’s plans for the regional center include mixed-use development on the vacant parcels in the northern section of the center, enhancements to the main street, and the creation of new open spaces that will provide direct connections to the river. The center is also home to Willamette Falls and the Willamette Falls Legacy Project, a public/private partnership working to connect the Falls to downtown through the development of housing, public spaces, habitat restoration, education and employment opportunities. The regional center also has access to Interstate 205 and Highway 213 and is served by seven TriMet bus lines and one Canby Area Transit bus line.

The Tanasbourne/AmberGlen Regional Center is located in Hillsboro. In 2010, the Tanasbourne Town Center was expanded to include the AmberGlen area and the designation was changed to a Regional Center. The area today has a mix of housing, commercial and office uses, including the Streets of Tanasbourne regional shopping center. The AmberGlen section of the center is dominated by suburban office park styled development, however more recently multifamily housing has been introduced to the area. This reflects the city’s aspirations to transition the area into an intensive mixed-used development that achieves higher levels of residential density. The regional center is served by multiple arterial roads and three TriMet bus lines, as well as a MAX Light Rail Blue Line stop on the southwestern border.

The Washington Square Regional Center is located on the border of Tigard and Beaverton and is divided by Highway 217 and numerous arterials. The regional center is anchored by the Washington Square Mall, a large shopping center, along with a number of other large retail, commercial and office facilities that have ample parking. The center contains a small amount of residences and also includes the City of Portland’s Red Tail Golf Center. The Westside Express Service Commuter Rail, seven TriMet bus lines and the Fanno Creek Regional Trail provide access to the center. The Washington Square Regional Plan calls for infill development that is mixed-use in nature, innovative transportation facilities that will make traveling throughout the center easy and a greenbelt of parks and trails.

The Aloha Town Center is located along Tualatin Valley Highway in unincorporated Washington County. While Tualatin Valley Highway provides access to the center, it along with the Portland and Western Railroad track is a controlling force that divides the town center. Single family homes are the predominant development pattern in the center with retail and employment clustered along Tualatin Valley Highway. Two TriMet bus lines provide transit access to the town center. A community plan for the larger Aloha-Reedville area calls for retaining the predominant residential character in the town center, while increasing density and locating the most intensive land use patterns at the intersection of Tualatin Valley Highway and 185th Avenue. Washington County is continuing to refine the plan for the town center.

The Bethany Town Center is located in northern unincorporated Washington County. The Bethany Community Plan calls for a mix of local retail and small community-based office uses that provide a community village atmosphere. The town center supports this vision with a mix of commercial and retail uses providing a wide range of services to the community as well as numerous housing options. Access to the town center is provided by NW Bethany Boulevard and one TriMet bus line.

The Cedar Mill Town Center is located in unincorporated Washington County, just north of Highway 26. It is bisected by NW Cornell Road, NW Murray Boulevard and SW Barnes Rd. TriMet bus lines on these major roads provide transit access to and within the center. Predominant uses today include auto-oriented retail and low-density single family homes. Future plans call for additional shopping and employment opportunities and nodes of medium and high-density residential development.

The Cornelius Town Center is located along Adair and Baseline Streets (Highway 8) between downtown Hillsboro and Forest Grove. Two Portland and Western Railroad tracks, one north and one south of Highway 8, traverse east-west through the town center. While auto-oriented development is the predominant land use along the highway, there is a significant amount of single family residences in the town center along with civic uses such as the library and city offices. The center is served by one TriMet bus line that connects to Forest Grove and additional transit options in Hillsboro, including the terminus of the MAX Light Rail Blue Line. Local plans highlight the desire to concentrate retail, businesses and civic uses along Adair and Baseline Streets in order to make the area more of a community focused destination and less of a thoroughfare.

The Damascus Town Center is located at the junction of SE Foster Road, SE Sunnyside Road and Highway 212 in the southeastern portion of the region. The Damascus area was included in the regional urban growth boundary in 2002 and to date no urban development has occurred in the town center. There is no transit service and the roads within Damascus are still at rural road standards.

The Fairview/Wood Village Town Center is located near the eastern edge of the region within the cities of Fairview and Wood Village. The town center is accessed by NE Halsey Street and NE 223rd Ave with transit connections through two TriMet bus lines along these arterials. The town center has two distinct patterns of development. The Fairview portion is defined by a compact residential and commercial development pattern that prioritizes walking and biking. The Wood Village portion of the town center is more auto-oriented with significant vacant and underutilized land and is currently undergoing a planning process that will set the future vision for that portion of the town center.

The Forest Grove Town Center is located on the western edge of the region in downtown Forest Grove. The town center is the heart of the community with cultural and commercial retail amenities, civic buildings and the main campus of Pacific University. A TriMet bus line and the GrovelLink Loop provide transit access in and around the town center. Strengthening downtown Forest Grove is a guiding principle in the city’s comprehensive plan by increasing densities in the area, while still ensuring that the historic nature of the downtown in preserved.

The Gladstone Town Center is located along Portland Avenue on what used to be a former streetcar line. The development pattern of the center is reminiscent of this, with small store fronts dotting much of the frontage along Portland Avenue and a single family residential neighborhood beyond. Gladstone High School anchors the northern edge of the town center and numerous civic uses such as the post office, fire and police departments and city hall are located on Portland Avenue. The town center is accessible via three TriMet bus lines. Gladstone has initiated a planning effort focused on revitalizing the town center.

The Happy Valley Town Center is located at the intersection of Southeast 162nd Avenue and Sunnyside Road in Happy Valley. The town center was moved in 2010 to the current location to allow for the opportunity to create a dense, compact town center dependent on walking, biking and transit. While the majority of the town center is still undeveloped, there is a shopping center, city hall and some single and multifamily housing. The area is currently served by one TriMet bus line, which runs through the western half of the center. The city’s vision for the center is for it to grow into a vibrant, multi-modal, town center area characterized by mixed land uses, expanded commercial opportunities, and varied residential densities supported by transportation patterns that allow easy walking, biking and transit connections.

The Hillsdale Town Center is located in the Hillsdale neighborhood of southwest Portland and is bisected by SW Capitol Highway (Highway 10). The town center features a mix of single and multi-family housing, commercial development focused along SW Capitol Highway, a library and Wilson High School and Rieke Elementary School. The center has six TriMet bus lines running through it and enhanced transit investment is being evaluated as part of the Southwest Corridor planning process.

The Hollywood Town Center is located along NE Sandy Boulevard in Portland. A compact core of uses, including retail, restaurants and medical services are concentrated along Sandy Boulevard. The center is walkable and has a mix of old buildings such as the Hollywood Theater and new multi-family housing development. MAX Light Rail (Red, Blue & Green lines) and three TriMet bus lines service the Hollywood Transit Center that is located on southern border of the town center adjacent to Interstate 84. The city’s vision for the center calls for recognizing and enhancing Hollywood’s local and regional commercial focus while encouraging more residents and a need for enhanced connections with the transit center. Recent development and investments in the center support the articulated vision.

The King City Town Center is located at the intersection of Highway 99W and SW Durham Road. Highway 99W bisects the town center and is a controlling force, resulting in auto-oriented commercial development as the predominant use along the highway. There are a few pockets of multi-family housing in the town center focused on senior living. The center is served by two TriMet bus lines that run along Highway 99W. The area just outside of the town center contains both single and multi-family housing. Local plans envision the area becoming a more walkable commercial district that will continue to be a valuable community asset.

The Lake Grove Town Center is located on the west side of Lake Oswego along Lower Boones Ferry Road, south of Kruse Way. A mix of retail and commercial services are concentrated along Lower Boones Ferry Road and Mercantile Drive. The Lake Grove Elementary School is within the town center and a concentration of housing can be found just beyond the center’s boundary. Local plans envision the town center as a pedestrian-friendly neighborhood community where nature and human activity are well connected and prosperously coexist. Two TriMet bus lines provide service to the town center.

The Lake Oswego Town Center is focused on N State Street (Highway 43) and A Ave and includes the majority of downtown and a significant amount of land along the Willamette River. The town center serves as the city’s main business district and provides a wide range of retail and commercial services as well as housing opportunities. Civic uses include city hall, the fire station and post office. The Portland and Western Railroad and the Willamette Shore Trolley tracks parallel N State Street, acting as a barrier for connections between downtown and the river. There are four TriMet bus lines that serve the town center.

The Lents Town Center in southeast Portland is centered along the SE Foster Road in the vicinity of the Interstate 205 interchange and includes area on both sides of the highway. Retail and commercial development is concentrated along SE Foster Road, with rest of the center comprised of predominantly single family homes. The center is an active urban renewal district with the Portland Development Commission owning a number of undeveloped parcels. The town center has three TriMet bus lines that travel through it, a MAX Light Rail Green Line station, and direct access to two regional trails, the 1-205 Trail and the Springwater Corridor Trail.

The Milwaukie Town Center is adjacent to McLoughlin Blvd (Highway 99E) and is comprised of historic downtown Milwaukie and the surrounding residential neighborhoods. Highway 224, which runs diagonally through the town center, has a shopping center and forms a barrier between the two main residential areas. The downtown area contains a mix of housing types and range of retail and commercial services, as well as a number of civic uses including city hall, the library, post office, Milwaukie Riverfront Park as well as multiple schools. The town center has nine TriMet bus lines that travel through it, a MAX Light Rail Orange Line station and direct access to the Trolley Trail.

The Murray/Scholls Town Center is located in Beaverton, just southwest of the intersection of SW Scholls Ferry Road and SW Murray Boulevard, which along with SW Barrows Road serve as the main points of access into the center. Additional access is provided by two TriMet bus lines on SW Scholls Ferry Road and the Westside Trail, a regional trail maintained by Tualatin Hills Park and Recreation District. There is a range of single and multifamily housing developments, as well as office and commercial uses in the Progress Ridge Townsquare development. Progress Lake provides a focal point for the town center.

The Orenco Town Center is located in Hillsboro along NE Cornell Road and has a wide range of housing types, small and large scale retail services and community parks. The Orenco Town Center has been lauded as a national example of transit oriented and new urbanist styled development. The town center is adjacent to a significant employment zone and is anchored by the Orenco MAX Light Rail Blue Line station at its southern edge. Two TriMet bus lines also provide transit service to the town center.

The Pleasant Valley Town Center is located in a rural area of unincorporated Multnomah County in the vicinity of SE Foster Road. The area was added to the urban growth boundary in 1998 and Portland and Gresham partnered to create a plan to transform the town center to a mixed-use, multimodal town center that functions as the heart of a future community. Currently no urban level development has occurred and there is no transit access to the town center.

The Raleigh Hill Town Center is located in unincorporated Washington County at the intersection of three major arterials, SW Beaverton-Hillsdale Highway (Highway 10), SW Scholls Ferry Road and SW Oleson Road, which results in an auto centric environment with commercial strip being the predominant development pattern. While this provides the community with a number of retail options and services, it diminishes the walkability of the town center. The community plan for this area emphasizes preserving the integrity of the surrounding residential neighborhoods and aims to reduce the continuation of commercial strip development. Four TriMet bus lines run through the town center.

The Rockwood Town Center is located in Gresham between NE 162nd and SE 202nd Avenues. There is a mix of single and multi-family housing spread throughout the center with auto-oriented commercial development focused along SE Stark Street. The center includes a library and numerous schools are located just beyond the town center boundary. The MAX Light Rail Blue Line runs along E Burnside Street through the middle of the town center and three TriMet bus lines also provide transit access. Future plans for the center envision it as a place with quality mixed-use development that promotes a 24-hour neighborhood that is integrally linked to transit.

The Sherwood Town Center is located at the intersection of Highway 99W and SW Tualatin-Sherwood Road. Highway 99W bisects the town center and auto-oriented commercial development is the predominant use in the center. Two TriMet bus lines provide service to the center. The land just outside of the center contains a significant amount of housing, providing a close in customer base. A town center plan completed in 2013 envisions this area as a walkable and active shopping district in the future, complete with more pedestrian-oriented buildings.

The St. Johns Town Center is centered along N Lombard Street in the St. Johns neighborhood in North Portland. The town center is compact and walkable with a mix of commercial development concentrated along N Lombard Street which functions as the neighborhood’s main street. There is a limited amount of old and new housing in the center, a post office, library and James John Elementary School. Cathedral Park and the iconic St. Johns Bridge, which includes the Peninsula Crossing Regional Trail, are adjacent to the south. The center is served by five TriMet bus lines. A town center plan for the area focuses on capitalizing on what is working well, while striving to become a more livable and economically viable place.

The Sunset Transit Town Center is located in unincorporated Washington County, adjacent to Highway 26. The center is accessible through a number of arterial roads, including Highway 26, Highway 217 and SW Barnes Road. Additionally it has transit access via five TriMet bus lines and MAX Light Rail Blue and Red lines, although the light rail station is separated from much of the housing and commercial development that is presently occurring in the center. This development is consistent with the community vision that the town center will include a mix of residential types and densities along with commercial and office uses.

The Tigard Town Center is located along Highway 99 W, north and south of Highway 217. Two styles of development exist in the center. The area surrounding SW Main Street is compact and walkable with a mix of local commercial and residential uses. City Hall and other city department offices are located near this portion of the town center and Fanno Creek Park provides a significant ribbon of green through the downtown. The Tigard Triangle portion of the center mostly contains auto-oriented retail and other employment uses. Portland and Western Railroad tracks cut through the town center and provide rail spurs to the adjacent employment land. The center is served by the Westside Express Commuter Rail Service, seven TriMet bus lines, and the Fanno Creek Regional Trail. The town center is being studied for future high-capacity transit investments through the regional Southwest Corridor planning process.

The Troutdale Town Center is located at the eastern edge of the region and extends from the Sandy River to McMenamins Edgefield. The town center includes Troutdale’s historic main street, residential neighborhoods and a retail outlet center. The historic main street offers a walkable environment with a variety of restaurants, retail and services, city hall, police station and a public plaza. There are a number of undeveloped or underdeveloped parcels in the town center with the larger ones owned by Multnomah County and the Reynolds School District. Union Pacific Railroad tracks run through the town center, however they are essentially below grade in the historic main street area. Three TriMet bus lines provide transit service.

The Tualatin Town Center is located at the intersection of SW Tualatin-Sherwood and SW Boones Ferry Roads. The town center pivots on the Lake on the Commons Park, which has public space, art and a mix of restaurants, retail businesses and housing. Civic uses within the center include the library, city offices and post office. The remainder of the center also has a mix of development types including a substantial amount of multi-family housing, office and large scale retail commercial uses. The town center has access to transit services via two TriMet bus lines and the Westside Express Service Commuter Rail.

The West Linn-Historic Willamette Town Center is located at the convergence of the Tualatin and Willamette Rivers and is divided by Interstate 205. The town center includes a commercial main street along Willamette Falls Drive with a single-family residential neighborhood to the south. Portions of the center are recognized on the National Register of Historic Places and included in the Main Street America Program run by the National Trust for Historic Preservation. The portion of the town center north of Interstate 205 includes office buildings, undeveloped land and a city owned park. One TriMet bus line provides transit access to the town center.

The West Linn-Bolton Town Center is located near the Willamette River and the Interstate 205-Willamette Drive (Highway 43) interchange. Commercial uses are concentrated along Willamette Drive, which runs through the middle of the center, with the remainder being single family homes. Civic uses include the library, post office, and city parks. The Bolton Primary School is within the town center and West Linn High School is directly west of the town center. Two TriMet bus lines provide transit access. Redevelopment plans call for soft infill development in parts of the center that keeps with the existing character. The portion of the center located between Interstate 205 and the Willamette River is slated for major changes, including mixed-use development.

The West Portland Town Center is located in southwest Portland at the intersection of Interstate 5, SW Capitol Highway and SW Barbur Boulevard (Highway 99W). Auto-oriented commercial development is concentrated along these major thoroughfares. The remainder of the town center is a mix of single- and multifamily housing. The center is currently served by three TriMet bus lines; however this area is currently being studied for high-capacity transit investments through the regional Southwest Corridor planning process.

The Wilsonville Town Center is centered on SW Wilsonville Road, directly adjacent to Interstate 5. Clustered single and multi-family housing along with the library is situated in the southern half of the center, adjacent to Memorial Park which extends to the Willamette River. The northern half is mainly large-lot commercial development, some undeveloped land and a very limited amount of multi-family housing. City Hall, the post office, Wilsonville Visitor Center and the Wilsonville Campus of Clackamas Community College are also located on the north side of the town center. SMART, Wilsonville’s own transit service operates two bus lines that provide transit access within the town center. The southern terminus of the Westside Express Service Commuter Rail is located just outside of the town center.
